        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>210358 is the brightest of the five galaxies studied with CARMA thus far. Measured integrated CO(1-0) flux is 11.1+/-1.1 Jy km/s, slightly above the predicted value of 7.6 from measured infrared luminosities (Greve et al. 2005). We estimate the total CO(3-2) emission by assuming that CO(3-2) is a factor of 6 higher than CO(1-0), already accounting for a typical dimming factor R_{3,1}=0.65 of LBGs (Baker et al. 2004, Danielson et al. 2011). To achieve sub-kpc scales, we request baseline configuration 5, which yields a synthesized beam resolution of 0.17 arcsec. That represents a physical scale of just above 400 pc per beam at z=0.137, which approximately matches the resolution of our IFU observations, and is less than 1/10th the resolution of existing CO observations of ScUVLGs.

We have used the AO-assisted Pa-alpha as a proxy for star formation in the galaxy, converted to gas surface density according to the Schmidt-Kennicutt relation, normalized to the predicted total flux (as discussed above). The diffuse Pa-alpha emission corresponds to a lower CO(3-2) flux threshold of approximately 1 mJy. At that resolution, that corresponds to a gas surface density threshold of approximately 100 Msun pc^-2, or 1/10th of the average value for the galaxy. We propose to observe with ALMA at an RMS level of 0.5 mJy; that will yield a 2-sigma detection of those faint regions, and &gt;=5-sigma detection of individual, denser star-forming regions.

The total proposal time lies at less than 3 hours to map the molecular gas at sub-kpc scales at redshift z=0.137. These numbers reflect the remarkable scientific yield of this project at very low cost made available by ALMA.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>At the redshift of 210358 (z=0.137), CO(3-2) lies at 303 GHz, well within band 7. In order to maximize signal-to-noise ratios in each channel, we will bin the data to a resolution of 10 km/s (or ~10 MHz), still much lower than typical line widths above ~50 km/s. This allows for a proper sampling of the line profile and subsequent comparison with kinematic maps obtained with IFU. For this purpose, the maximum channel spacing of 488 kHz with dual polarization is beyond sufficient for our purposes, while the total bandwidth of 1875 MHz (~1800 km/s) ensures we can determine the complete profile of the emission line.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have used the Pa-alpha derived map to simulate observations with the simalma task in CASA, using the same integration time as required to achieve 0.5 mJy rms. We show the results in Figure 3. The simulated map shows we can indeed study the substructure of molecular gas within the galaxy in detail. Therefore, the requested Cycle 3 configuration (5) is ideal for our needs. At the same time, the maximum scale probed by the minimum baseline in this configuration is 2 arcsec, approximately the same as the physical size of our target, dispensing the use of the ACA.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
